{{Psychoanalysis |Training}} '''Boston Graduate School of Psychoanalysis''' is a [[Private education|private]] educational institution that focuses on training [[Psychoanalysis|psychoanalysts]], particularly in the field of [[modern psychoanalysis]]. Founded in 1973, it only awards graduate degrees. Its main campus is in [[Brookline, Massachusetts]].
== Accreditation == The Boston Graduate School of Psychoanalysis, including its branch campus in [[New York City|New York]], is accredited by the [[New England Association of Schools and Colleges]], Inc. through its Commission on Institutions of Higher Education. It first received accreditation from the [[New England Association of Schools and Colleges]] (NEASC) in 1995, which opened psychoanalytic study to any qualified and engaged student irrespective of prior courses of study.<ref name=NEASC>{{cite web|title=NEASC|url=http://cihe.neasc.org/about_our_institutions/roster_of_institutions/details/19687|accessdate=18 January 2013}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
Boston Graduate School of Psychoanalysis is the only regionally accredited school of psychoanalytic studies in the United States to grant graduate degrees.<ref name="Hyman Spotnitz" group=book>{{cite book|last=Spotnitz|first=Hyman|title=Modern psychoanalysis of the schizophrenic patient:Theory of the technique|year=2004|publisher=YBK Pub Inc.|location=NY, NY|isbn=0-9703923-6-2|pages=preface|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KmQU3XjJLvgC&pg=PP5 }}</ref>
